<subSubSection id="F2EA05A8410AFFA6FF1D0BC58B49F9B4" pageId="5" pageNumber="32" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="BA4F5623410AFFA6FF1D0BC58B49F9B4" blockId="5.[151,1437,1449,2036]" pageId="5" pageNumber="32">
<emphasis id="88848A31410AFFA6FF1D0BC58B29F99B" bold="true" box="[197,330,1529,1555]" pageId="5" pageNumber="32">Etymology</emphasis>
. A combination of the Latin words: longus and barba, referring to the long filar-like processes of aedeagus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="F2EA05A8410AFFA6FF1D08758876F93C" pageId="5" pageNumber="32" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="BA4F5623410AFFA6FF1D08758876F93C" blockId="5.[151,1437,1449,2036]" pageId="5" pageNumber="32">
<emphasis id="88848A31410AFFA6FF1D08758B26F9EB" bold="true" box="[197,325,1609,1635]" pageId="5" pageNumber="32">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Fore tarsomeres with longer fringe-like setae on anterior surface; surstylus deeply bifurcated distally, with minute scale-like processes (Fig. 
<number id="0C384404410AFFA6FD1D084E8886F904" box="[709,741,1650,1676]" pageId="5" pageNumber="32" value="13.0">13</number>
); aedeagus with 
<number id="0C384404410AFFA6FC75084E89DFF904" box="[941,956,1650,1676]" pageId="5" pageNumber="32" value="4.0">4</number>
pairs of rod-like processes, one of them twice as long as others (Fig. 
<number id="0C384404410AFFA6FE3E08A68864F93C" box="[486,519,1690,1716]" pageId="5" pageNumber="32" value="14.0">14</number>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="F2EA05A8410AFFA5FF1D08FD89A5FF52" lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="33" pageId="5" pageNumber="32" type="description">
<paragraph id="BA4F5623410AFFA6FF1D08FD8831F82C" blockId="5.[151,1437,1449,2036]" pageId="5" pageNumber="32">
<emphasis id="88848A31410AFFA6FF1D08FD8B36F953" bold="true" box="[197,341,1729,1755]" pageId="5" pageNumber="32">Description</emphasis>
. Male. Frons and fronto-orbital plate brown. Palpus black. Mesonotum and scutellum yellow brown, without patches and longitudinal stripes. Postpronotal lobe yellow brown on upper 
<number id="0C384404410AFFA6FB6208D68EABF88C" box="[1210,1224,1770,1796]" pageId="5" pageNumber="32" value="3.0">3</number>
/ 
<number id="0C384404410AFFA6FB0A08D68E82F88C" box="[1234,1249,1770,1796]" pageId="5" pageNumber="32" value="5.0">5</number>
, white on lower 
<number id="0C384404410AFFA6FF4F092E8AC4F8A4" box="[151,167,1810,1836]" pageId="5" pageNumber="32" value="2.0">2</number>
/ 
<number id="0C384404410AFFA6FF69092E8ADCF8A4" box="[177,191,1810,1836]" pageId="5" pageNumber="32" value="5.0">5</number>
. Katepisternum nearly brown. Legs almost brown, pale on all tarsomeres. Fore femur with 
<number id="0C384404410AFFA6FAF8092E8F4CF8A4" box="[1312,1327,1810,1836]" pageId="5" pageNumber="32" value="4.0">4</number>
setae on median of ventral surface; fore tarsomeres with longer fringe-like setae on anterior surface. Abdominal all tergites and sternites brown. Cercus with sporadic pubescence (Fig. 
<number id="0C384404410AFFA6FC6D095E89B5F8F4" box="[949,982,1890,1916]" pageId="5" pageNumber="32" value="12.0">12</number>
). Plate between hypandrium and aedeagus with a few pubescence (Fig. 
<number id="0C384404410AFFA6FDFD09B68826F82C" box="[549,581,1930,1956]" pageId="5" pageNumber="32" value="14.0">14</number>
).
</paragraph>
